snow.types.AudioInfo.name: AudioInfo
snow.types.AudioInfo.doc:
Information about an audio file/data

`id` : file source
`format` : format
`channels` : number of channels
`rate` : hz rate
`bitrate` : sound bitrate
`bits_per_sample` : bits per sample, 8 / 16
`data` : sound raw data,
`length` : the file length in bytes
`length_pcm` : the pcm uncompressed raw length in bytes
`handle` : the native audio handle for later manipulation

members.name: antialiasing

snow.io.IO.name: IO
snow.io.IO.doc:
This class is a low level cross platform IO helper.
    If you want file access, use `Assets` instead, unless really required.

methods.name: url_open
methods.doc: Opens the specified url in the default browser

methods.name: from_file
methods.doc: Create an `IOFile` from a file path `_id`, this bypasses the `Asset` system path helpers.

methods.name: watch_add
methods.doc: Add a folder to a watch list for notifications when the contents of the folder change

methods.name: watch_remove
methods.doc: Remove a folder from the watch list

methods.name: dialog_open
methods.doc: Opens a file open dialog. Returns a blank string if they cancel or any error occurs.

methods.name: dialog_save
methods.doc: Opens a file save file dialog. Returns a blank string if they cancel or any error occurs.

methods.name: dialog_folder
methods.doc: Opens a file open folder select dialog. Returns a blank string if they cancel or any error occurs.

methods.name: typed
methods.doc: returns a typed `InputEventType` from an integer ID, for communication between internal native + haxe code

methods.name: getHeader
methods.doc: Returns the PNG header informations. Throws an exception if no header found.

methods.name: getPalette
methods.doc: Return the PNG palette colors, or null if no palette chunk was found

methods.name: reverseBytes
methods.doc: Converts from BGRA to ARGB and the other way by reversing bytes.

methods.name: extractGrey
methods.doc: Decode the greyscale PNG data and apply filters, extracting only the grey channel if alpha is present.

methods.name: extract32
methods.doc: Decode the PNG data and apply filters. By default this will output BGRA low-endian format. You can use the [reverseBytes] function to inverse the bytes to ARGB big-endian format.

methods.name: buildGrey
methods.doc: Creates PNG data from bytes that contains one bytes (grey values) for each pixel.

methods.name: buildRGB
methods.doc: Creates PNG data from bytes that contains three bytes (R,G and B values) for each pixel.

methods.name: build32ARGB
methods.doc: Creates PNG data from bytes that contains four bytes in ARGB format for each pixel.

methods.name: build32BGRA
methods.doc: Creates PNG data from bytes that contains four bytes in BGRA format for each pixel.

snow.io.IOFile.name: IOFile
snow.io.IOFile.doc:
This class is a low level cross platform file access helper, that handles in bundle assets etc.
    If you want a file, use `Assets` instead, unless really required.

members.name: handle
members.doc: The internal native file handle

methods.name: read
methods.doc: Read a `maxnum` of items of `size` in bytes, into `dest`. Same signature/returns as `fread`

methods.name: write
methods.doc: Write `num` of items of `size` in bytes, from `src` into this file. Same signature/returns as `fwrite`

methods.name: seek
methods.doc: Seek `offset` from `whence`, where whence is an int matching `set=0`, `cur=1`, `end=2`. Same signature/returns as `fseek`

methods.name: tell
methods.doc: Tell the current position in the file, in bytes

methods.name: close
methods.doc: Close the file

snow.CoreBinding.name: CoreBinding
snow.CoreBinding.doc:
Implemented in the platform specific concrete versions of this class.

This uses a macro to allow this class to pretend to be abstract, and complain via compiler errors if the specific functions are missing.

methods.name: init
methods.doc: Called by the snow internals to intiialize the core and subsystems of the framework, with the event handler passed in for where to deliver system events

methods.name: shutdown
methods.doc: Called to explicitly shutdown the framework cleanly. Called by `quit` and `app_terminated` type events by the core, for example.

methods.name: timestamp
methods.doc: Get the most precise timestamp available on the platform, in seconds (time is always in seconds in snow)

methods.name: app_path
methods.doc: Return the full path that the application is located

methods.name: pref_path
methods.doc: On platforms where this makes sense, get the application specific writeable data path

members.name: id
members.doc: the window id, for tracking events to each window

members.name: manager
members.doc: the manager this window belongs to

members.name: asked_config
members.doc: the requested window config

members.name: config
members.doc: the actual returned window config

members.name: handle
members.doc: the native window handle

members.name: onevent
members.doc: the window event handler callback

members.name: onrender
members.doc: the window render handler callback

members.name: windowed_fullscreen
members.doc: set this for fullscreen windowed mode, instead of fullscreen mode

members.name: auto_swap
members.doc: set this if you want to control when a window swaps() where applicable

methods.name: swap
methods.doc: Swap the back buffer of the window, call after rendering to update the window view

methods.name: close
methods.doc: Close the window

methods.name: simple_message
methods.doc: Display a cross platform message on this window

snow.AppFixedTimestep.name: AppFixedTimestep
snow.AppFixedTimestep.doc:
Read the {App Guide} for full info, and for even more information see : http://gafferongames.com/game-physics/fix-your-timestep/
    this stores and calculates a fixed game update loop, and rendering interpolation is required
    for smooth updates between frames.

members.name: frame_time
members.doc: fixed simulation update speed

members.name: overflow
members.doc: the overflow of the updates. This is used internally, for you, to calculate the alpha time for rendering interpolation as follows `alpha = overflow / frame_time;`

snow.App.name: App
snow.App.doc: The default type of application, with variable delta time, or fixed delta time, or a fixed frame rate. See the {App Guide} for complete details.

members.name: timescale

members.name: delta_sim

members.name: current_time

members.name: cur_frame_start

members.name: alpha

members.name: next_tick
members.doc: for update_rate, the time when the next tick should occur around

members.name: next_render

methods.name: config
methods.doc:
Called by snow to request config changes, override this to change the defaults.
            This happens before ready, so the values are available when ready is called.

methods.name: ready
methods.doc: Your entry point. Called for you when you can initialize your application

methods.name: update
methods.doc: Your update loop. Called every frame for you. The dt value depends on the timing configuration (see the {App Guide})

methods.name: destroyed
methods.doc: Your exit point. Called for you when you should shut down your application

methods.name: on_event
methods.doc: Low level event handler from snow core. Often handled by the subsystems so check there first.

methods.name: onkeydown
methods.doc: Called for you when a key is pressed down

methods.name: onkeyup
methods.doc: Called for you when a key is released

methods.name: ontextinput
methods.doc: Called for you when text input is happening. Use this for textfields, as it handles the complexity of unicode etc.

methods.name: onmousedown
methods.doc: Called for you when a mouse button is pressed

methods.name: onmouseup
methods.doc: Called for you when a mouse button is released

methods.name: onmousewheel
methods.doc: Called for you when the mouse wheel moves

methods.name: onmousemove
methods.doc: Called for you when the mouse moves

methods.name: ontouchdown
methods.doc: Called for you when a touch is released, use the `touch_id` to track which

methods.name: ontouchup
methods.doc: Called for you when a touch is first pressed, use the `touch_id` to track which

methods.name: ontouchmove
methods.doc: Called for you when a touch is moved, use the `touch_id` to track which

methods.name: ongamepadaxis
methods.doc: Called for you when a connected gamepad axis moves, use `which` to determine gamepad id

methods.name: ongamepadbuttondown
methods.doc: Called for you when a connected gamepad button is pressed, use `which` to determine gamepad id

methods.name: ongamepadbuttonup
methods.doc: Called for you when a connected gamepad button is released, use `which` to determine gamepad id

methods.name: ongamepaddevice
methods.doc: Called for you when a gamepad is connected or disconnected, use `which` to determine gamepad id

methods.name: new
methods.doc: The default constructor of an App is empty, so you can override it if you want, but take note that this happens way before snow is ready for use. Use [ready](#ready) for entry point.

members.doc: If the assets are not relative to the runtime root path, this value can adjust all asset paths. This is automatically handled and exists to allow control.

snow.input.Scancodes.name: Scancodes
snow.input.Scancodes.doc:
The scancode class. The values below come directly from SDL header include files,
but they aren't specific to SDL so they are used generically

members.name: BACKSLASH
members.doc:
Located at the lower left of the return
    key on ISO keyboards and at the right end
    of the QWERTY row on ANSI keyboards.
    Produces REVERSE SOLIDUS (backslash) and
    VERTICAL LINE in a US layout, REVERSE
    SOLIDUS and VERTICAL LINE in a UK Mac
    layout, NUMBER SIGN and TILDE in a UK
    Windows layout, DOLLAR SIGN and POUND SIGN
    in a Swiss German layout, NUMBER SIGN and
    APOSTROPHE in a German layout, GRAVE
    ACCENT and POUND SIGN in a French Mac
    layout, and ASTERISK and MICRO SIGN in a
    French Windows layout.

members.name: NONUSHASH
members.doc:
ISO USB keyboards actually use this code
    instead of 49 for the same key, but all
    OSes I've seen treat the two codes
    identically. So, as an implementor, unless
    your keyboard generates both of those
    codes and your OS treats them differently,
    you should generate public static var BACKSLASH
    instead of this code. As a user, you
    should not rely on this code because SDL
    will never generate it with most (all?)
    keyboards.

members.name: GRAVE
members.doc:
Located in the top left corner (on both ANSI
    and ISO keyboards). Produces GRAVE ACCENT and
    TILDE in a US Windows layout and in US and UK
    Mac layouts on ANSI keyboards, GRAVE ACCENT
    and NOT SIGN in a UK Windows layout, SECTION
    SIGN and PLUS-MINUS SIGN in US and UK Mac
    layouts on ISO keyboards, SECTION SIGN and
    DEGREE SIGN in a Swiss German layout (Mac:
    only on ISO keyboards); CIRCUMFLEX ACCENT and
    DEGREE SIGN in a German layout (Mac: only on
    ISO keyboards), SUPERSCRIPT TWO and TILDE in a
    French Windows layout, COMMERCIAL AT and
    NUMBER SIGN in a French Mac layout on ISO
    keyboards, and LESS-THAN SIGN and GREATER-THAN
    SIGN in a Swiss German, German, or French Mac
    layout on ANSI keyboards.

members.name: INSERT
members.doc: insert on PC, help on some Mac keyboards (but does send code 73, not 117)

members.name: NUMLOCKCLEAR
members.doc: num lock on PC, clear on Mac keyboards

members.name: NONUSBACKSLASH
members.doc:
This is the additional key that ISO
    keyboards have over ANSI ones,
    located between left shift and Y.
    Produces GRAVE ACCENT and TILDE in a
    US or UK Mac layout, REVERSE SOLIDUS
    (backslash) and VERTICAL LINE in a
    US or UK Windows layout, and
    LESS-THAN SIGN and GREATER-THAN SIGN
    in a Swiss German, German, or French
    layout.

members.name: POWER

The USB document says this is a status flag,

snow.utils.AbstractClass.name: AbstractClass
snow.utils.AbstractClass.doc:
Old school abstract class.
	Classes that implements it, and their sub-classes, will be able to declare abstract methods (methods that without body).
	There will be a check in compile-time such that no public constructor is allowed without all abstract methods implemented.
